00:39.637 --> 00:41.839
Jersey. Went through high school at Newark, New 
Jersey. That was in 1946 I graduated. Went into the

00:50.437 --> 00:54.685
Army, mostly to get the GI Bill, which I got. And 
when I got out of the service in 1948, the folks had

00:55.787 --> 01:01.719
moved to California, Southern California. And so 
I went to UCLA using my GI Bill and started off as an

01:02.520 --> 01:10.015
electrical engineering major. And because of the 
rigidity there was in selecting classes for

01:10.619 --> 01:21.399
electrical engineering majors at that time, I 
decided being an electrical engineer was not what

01:10.619 --> 01:21.399
I wanted to do. So I went over to the physics 
department and became a physics major. And when I

01:26.093 --> 01:39.171
got my degree after more than the four years, 
because I was working all the time, as well as the GI

01:26.093 --> 01:39.171
Bill, I was working all the time to work my way 
through college. And so I ended up graduating with

01:39.872 --> 01:47.022
165 credit hours rather than the usual 120. But 
nevertheless, when I graduated, Ken McKenzie of

01:47.204 --> 01:57.036
the physics department invited me to be a teaching 
assistant. And I took him up on it, became a

01:57.556 --> 02:05.005
graduate teaching assistant, and finished 
getting a master's and PhD at UCLA. Officially got

02:06.006 --> 02:09.010
the PhD in 1960. I officially graduated with a 
bachelor's degree from UCLA in 1952,

02:09.648 --> 02:26.278
got the master's degree in 1953, and officially 
the PhD in 1960, although I had finished up in 1959.

02:26.418 --> 02:31.026
It was a question of writing the dissertation and 
getting it approved. I went to work for Space

02:33.526 --> 02:37.510
General, or it was Space Electronics, it was 
called at that time. It was a company run by Jim

02:37.970 --> 02:50.381
Fletcher, who later became the president of the 
University of Utah, and Frank Leehan, who later

02:37.970 --> 02:50.381
became Secretary of Transportation in Johnson's 
administration. And we worked on weapons

02:50.922 --> 03:01.491
systems, communications, self-focusing 
antenna arrays, underground communication,

03:02.062 --> 03:06.429
side-looking radar, synthetic aperture radar, 
and a lot of those things. And I found it very

03:06.449 --> 03:07.931
interesting. The only problem was I was always 
working on war machines. And I figured I didn't

03:12.238 --> 03:19.449
spend all those years going to school to be working 
on war machines or things like that. So I decided to

03:19.489 --> 03:26.500
leave and go back to the academia. I was fortunate 
enough to get a position at MIT in their geology and

03:26.868 --> 03:32.774
geophysics department. I spent three years 
there. That was in 1964 through 67. And got to meet

03:37.899 --> 03:42.323
some very fine people. Ray Hyde, who is now at the 
British Meteorological Office. I suppose he's

03:47.788 --> 03:49.450
retired by now. Nafi Toxos, who's still at MIT. And 
Frank Press became department head. There were

03:55.015 --> 03:58.579
really a bunch of super people. Ted Madden is 
another one who probably retired by now. And

04:02.664 --> 04:09.632
