curriculum that was very applied geophysics 
oriented. We have done some things in global

24:58.755 --> 25:02.179
geophysics. But the major part of it has been in 
exploration geophysics, certainly at the

25:02.159 --> 25:09.127
undergraduate level and at the master's level. 
When you get to the PhD level, why then the problems

25:09.147 --> 25:15.574
almost have to be more global than exploration. So 
because of that, having very good students, and

25:16.175 --> 25:24.184
the oil companies were looking for good students, 
they would come and they would recruit. And so

25:24.164 --> 25:27.669
whenever they came and recruited, we said, look 
it, you want good students? We can get good

25:28.249 --> 25:30.192
students, but we need money. Give us the money and 
we'll get good students. You're not doing us any

25:32.896 --> 25:35.419
favors by giving us the money. Well, they really 
were, of course, because we were getting better

25:35.780 --> 25:38.623
students. I said, you know, because you're just 
making more work for us, right? I said, but if you do

25:41.587 --> 25:47.195
that, why, then we'll have good quality students 
when you come here to recruit. And they were very,

25:47.615 --> 25:51.741
very generous in that regard. Are there some oil 
companies that deserve special mention that were

25:51.721 --> 25:56.907
more generous? Yeah, let's see. I believe Amoco 
was one of them that was really very active. And

26:04.897 --> 26:08.982
Phillips Petroleum was also a good one. And Shell

26:09.002 --> 26:13.307
was very helpful. The others were also helpful, 
but not quite as much. But those people were very,

26:17.793 --> 26:19.756
very active. As a matter of fact, Gary Servos of 
Amoco would come and actually set up seismic

26:20.057 --> 26:28.208
chutes in the area for the students and things of 
that sort. It was really tremendous. In the late

26:29.991 --> 26:42.889
60s and early 70s, for geosciences undergraduate 
students, what were the tough courses, either

26:29.991 --> 26:42.889
within the department or outside, that were kind 
of the gateway courses? Well,

26:43.949 --> 27:05.721
for our students there weren't many tough courses 
in the first two years and part of the problem there

26:43.949 --> 27:05.721
was that we didn't have any geophysics courses in 
the first two years because they were all taking

26:43.949 --> 27:05.721
the chemistry, physics, and math that We felt that 
a geophysicist, as well as geology. We had some

27:08.804 --> 27:12.488
good, tough geology courses that they were 
teaching them. And as a matter of fact, that was one

27:13.028 --> 27:21.577
thing that we had to do something about because we 
hardly got to see our students until they were

27:13.028 --> 27:21.577
juniors. And by that time, they were being stolen 
away from us because all these other people had

27:22.217 --> 27:28.644
seen them and saw what great students they were. 
They recruited them for their department. So we

27:31.827 --> 27:34.189
set up some courses. at the freshman level and the 
sophomore level, for the geophysics majors. They

27:41.900 --> 27:45.903
were solid courses, but we weren't trying to do any 
weeding. We were trying to do some retention.

27:48.406 --> 27:53.090
Actually, we never did any real weeding in trying 
to do that. If there was any attrition, the

27:54.291 --> 28:01.557
attrition was natural by the chemistry, the 
physics, and the math courses, which are tough

27:54.291 --> 28:01.557
courses. They would compete with the physicists, 
mathematicians, and the engineers. Let's make

28:07.362 --> 28:13.218
believe you were an undergraduate advisor in that 
period. What courses, if a student came in for

28:14.722 --> 28:23.346
advice, what freshman and sophomore courses did 
you look at most carefully to see how they had done?

28:24.338 --> 28:26.322
Oh, I looked at their math and physics courses. 
Math and physics. Oh, yes, primarily. And also

28:30.110 --> 28:42.735
their English course that they took as well, 
because that's one of the things that we found at

28:30.110 --> 28:42.735
that time, and it's still true, it's even more true 
now, is that the greatest training these kids

28:30.110 --> 28:42.735
needed was in communication. And being 
geophysicists, they weren't really scientists

28:42.715 --> 28:47.802
in the pure scientist sense. These were guys who 
were going to be applied scientists. And as

28:50.566 --> 28:53.050
applied scientists, therefore, they had to 
communicate. And furthermore, if they were going

28:53.370 --> 29:03.945
to go into the oil business, what they were 
supposed to do was work up a prospect and make a

28:53.370 --> 29:03.945
convincing story to management that this 
prospect was a good one, that they should drill it,

28:53.370 --> 29:03.945
and so forth and so on. So communications was very 
important. So very early in the game, we looked at

29:06.349 --> 29:11.997
their English grades. In those early years, how 
adequate were the classrooms and laboratory

29:11.977 --> 29:21.151
facilities for teaching and research in 
geophysics? The ones that were in our department

29:23.094 --> 29:27.240
were fine. It was really not very difficult. There 
weren't very many students, though, because at

29:29.423 --> 29:35.172
the peak, I think we had maybe 30 students in a 
class. So it was always a small program. And given

29:39.382 --> 29:45.990
that the program is that small, you've got 15 kids 
in a class, there's no way that you can do anything

29:39.382 --> 29:45.990
but a quality program. You really would have to be a 
bad teacher not to do a good job with that few

29:47.071 --> 29:56.843
students, especially when they were very bright 
students, which is what they were. What was the

29:57.303 --> 30:03.691
normal workload for you in terms of hours to teach 
per semester during those early years? I

30:04.852 --> 30:07.836
generally taught two courses per semester. And 
sometimes I would do three, but the third one would

30:08.288 --> 30:17.081
be a seminar or something like that, which really 
didn't take a lot of time and effort. Later on, I

30:17.542 --> 30:18.764
taught more. But the teaching load has always been 
very, very light in geophysics. The idea was that

30:23.751 --> 30:28.117
we were supposed to, they expected us to do 
research. They expected us to get research

30:28.598 --> 30:31.883
grants. They expected us to have graduate 
students, because you supported the graduate

30:31.863 --> 30:38.351
students with research grants and so forth and so 
on. And so there was that. So the teaching load, I

30:40.133 --> 30:44.859
think, was quite light, my personal opinion. And 
within the department, were good standards set in

30:45.780 --> 30:56.132
those early years for the faculty in terms of 
promotion and tenure and so forth? Oh, I think so. I

30:59.001 --> 31:06.877
remember I had to make a big deal and threaten to 
leave in order to get my promotion, but I got it. I

31:06.917 --> 31:08.641
wasn't too old. I think I was 40 years old or 
something like that. So I guess if I hadn't

31:11.166 --> 31:15.876
threatened, I probably would have gotten it in the 
next year.

